[49m[39m  452, 452[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m  453, 453[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Why This Isn't Production-Ready
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This architecture covers the core graph traversal and state management loop. But several production concerns remain unaddressed:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **HL7/FHIR integration testing.** The EventBridge integration assumes clean, well-structured clinical events. Real EHR feeds (HL7v2 ADT messages, FHIR Subscription notifications) arrive with missing fields, duplicate deliveries, out-of-order timestamps, and encoding quirks. You need an integration test suite that replays captured HL7v2 message streams against the State Updater Lambda and validates that pathway state transitions match expected behavior. Budget 3-4 weeks just for edge cases in message parsing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Pathway authoring UI.** This recipe assumes pathway definitions arrive as structured JSON. In practice, clinical committees author pathways in narrative documents, Visio diagrams, or proprietary pathway editors. You need a tool that lets clinicians (not engineers) build and validate pathway graphs visually, with guardrails that enforce structural rules (exactly one start node, decision points need multiple branches). Without this, every pathway update requires an engineer to hand-translate a PDF into graph JSON.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical committee governance workflow.** Pathways change. Evidence evolves, formularies shift, and outcomes data reveals better approaches. Production needs a governance workflow: propose a pathway change, route it through clinical committee review, stage it for testing, validate it against synthetic patients, and then promote it to production, all while patients already on the old version continue uninterrupted. Version management is the easy part; organizational buy-in for the governance process is the hard part.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-pathway conflict detection.** A patient on three simultaneous pathways can receive contradictory recommendations (one says fluid bolus, another says fluid restriction). This architecture treats each pathway independently. Production needs a conflict detection layer that checks new recommendations against all active pathways before surfacing them to clinicians.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Graceful degradation under EHR outage.** If the FHIR endpoint goes down, condition evaluation fails. The system should degrade to showing pathway position without real-time condition status, rather than returning errors or stale recommendations without indicating staleness.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
